[![Text Editor][1]][1]

Oracle has a helpful tutorial, [Creating a GUI With Swing](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/index.html).  Skip the Learning Swing with the NetBeans IDE section.  

When creating a `JFrame`, you pack the `JFrame` and set the `JFrame` visible last.  You do not set the size of the `JFrame`.  The `JFrame` will size based on the components you&#39;re displaying.

I added row and column counts to your `JTextArea`.  This allows the BorderLayout to size itself properly. 

If you want the `JButtons` to display under the `JTextArea`, you have to use a different Swing layout.

