Looks like you need to use *partial mocking* approach. 

For example, you have class with 2 methods. *MethodB* is called from *MethodA*.
```java
public class Example {

    public int methodA(int a) {
        return methodB(a);
    }

    public int methodB(int a) {
        return a + a;
    }
}
```

Test with mocking methodB will look like this. Use thenAnswer method to get arguments from invocation and return result based on it
```java
@Test
void sampleTest() {
    Example classUnderTest = Mockito.spy(new Example());

    Mockito.when(classUnderTest.methodA(10)).thenAnswer(invocation -&gt; {
        Integer firstArgument = invocation.getArgument(0);
        return firstArgument * firstArgument;
    });

    assertEquals(100, classUnderTest.methodA(10));
}
```

Keep in mind that it will not work with private and static methods, for these ones use special library powermock etc.

